  "doc_id": "39795",
  "text": "Some neural activities contain both an ERP component as well as an oscillatory component. One particular example of this is the movement-related cortical potential (MRCP), which can be elicited by voluntary movements of the hands and feet and is observable through EEG along the central and midline electrodes, contralateral to the hand or foot movement [CITATION_1] . The oscillatory component of the MRCP can be seen both before movement onset (an early desynchronization in the 10-12Hz frequency band) as well as after movement onset (a late synchronization of 20-30Hz activity approximately 1s after movement execution). The ERP component of the MRCP occurs at the start of the movement, with a duration of approximately 800ms. The MRCP has been used previously to develop motor control BCIs for both healthy and physically disabled patients [CITATION_2] .",
